cle" id="RA1" vol="33" elocation-id="e327" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xlink:href="30505258" ext-link-type="pubmed"><article-title>Discordance between Physician and the General Public Perceptions of Prognostic Disclosure to Children with Serious Illness: a Korean Nationwide Study</article-title></related-article></article-meta></front><body><p>To the Editor,</p><p>The authors regret that approval number of Institutional Review Board (IRB) was wrong in the following article: &#x0201c;Discordance between Physician and the General Public Perceptions of Prognostic Disclosure to Children with Serious Illness: a Korean Nationwide Study,&#x0201d; <italic>J Korean Med Sci</italic> 2018;33(49):e327.</p><p><bold>Ethics statement</bold></p><p>This study was approved by the Institutional Review Board (IRB) of each hospital (Seoul National University Hospital IRB No. <underline>E-1612-102-815</underline>). Informed consent was submitted by all subjects when they were enrolled. We conducted the study in accordance with the principles of the Declaration of Helsinki.</p><p>The correct Ethics statement is:</p><p><bold>Ethics statement</bold></p><p>This study was approved by the Institutional Review Board (IRB) of each hospital (Seoul National University Hospital IRB No. <underline>E-1607-107-777</underline>). Informed consent was submitted by all subjects when they were enrolled. We conducted the study in accordance with the principles of the Declaration of Helsinki.</p></body></article>